US rates twist- flatten, supportedly firm GDP data; key events for Fed leadership in the coming week; S&P 500 at record highs; JGBs rally on BoJ statements suggesting potential rate hike delays; Polish fiscal concerns; DXY at 97.813 (- 0.4%); US 10y at 4.206% (- 3.0bp).

- US rates twist flatten in a partial unwinding of recent steepening. Front-end Treasuries sell off modestly (2y: +2bp), supported by an upside surprise in 2Q GDP, revised up to 3.3% (C: 3.1%; P: 3.0%) on stronger-than-expected business investment, and slightly weak initial jobless claims (229k; C: 230k) and continuing jobless claims (1,954k; C: 1,966k). Long-end Treasuries rally (30y: -5bp), potentially aided by demand from portfolio duration extensions before the end of the month. The 7y auction in the afternoon tails by 0.3bp, but high allocation to indirect bidders conveys decent demand.

- USD weakens (DXY: -0.4%) and gold rallies 0.6% as Fed leadership remains in focus. Fed Governor Cook files a lawsuit seeking a temporary restraining order to prevent her removal, with an emergency hearing scheduled to begin at 10:00am EST on Friday. After markets close, the US Senate Banking Committee schedules Miran's initial hearing for September 4, after which both the committee and the full Senate must vote to confirm Miran by simple majority, with media reports suggesting he will likely be confirmed before the September meeting.

- Risk-sensitive currencies outperform the dollar weakness (USD/SEK - 0.6%, AUD/USD +0.4%, NZD/USD +0.5%). The safe-haven JPY gains 0.3% against USD, despite delays in US-Japan trade discussions as Japanese officials canceled planned visit. USD/NOK weakens 0.2% as oil prices trend upwards (percent +0.8%) amid continued military activity between Russia and Ukraine, with German Chancellor Merz suggesting that there will be no meeting between Russian President Putin and Ukrainian President Zelensky.

- US equities extend their rally, appearing to look through domestic political developments. The S&P 500 gains 0.3% to a record high of over \$6,500 after highly anticipated large-cap tech earnings signal impacts from US-China trade restrictions, but also continued strong demand for AI spending. Accordingly, the tech-exposed NASDAQ 100 (+0.6%) outperforms the S&P 500.

CEEMEA rates see mixed performance in a quiet session, with Poland underperforming on fiscal concerns. The Polish government increases its 2025 fiscal deficit forecast to \(6.9\%\) of GDP (P: \(5.5\%\) ), driven by high defense, welfare, and debt servicing costs. Accordingly, Polish rates sell off \(\sim 5bp\) across the curve.

Rates and equities rally in several LatAm economies. In Brazil, equities rally (Ibovespa: \(+1.6\%\) ) as President Lula states he may not seek reelection if he is not in good health amid new polls showing lower approval ratings for his administration. BRL gains \(0.2\%\) against USD as local interest rate futures rally (Jan 31 D1: - 13bp). In Mexico, rates rally 5- 6bp across the curve, despite a slight downside surprise in July unemployment (2.77%; C: 2.86%; P: 2.69%). The government proposes plans to increase tariffs on Chinese imports, potentially strengthening relations with the US ahead of the 2026 review of the USMCA free trade agreement. Our Mexico economists revised their forecasts to incorporate faster rate cuts from Banxico, in line with the US.

Japanese rates rally modestly as Boj policymakers imply potential delays to rate hikes. In the Tokyo morning, 30y JGBs rally 2bp, seemingly driven by expectations of further issuance reductions in long- end sectors. Boj Board Member Nakagawa mentions in a speech that the Tankan survey, released October 1, will be "important to monitor." Accordingly, market participants infer that a September rate hike is less likely. 2y JGBs initially rally, but retrace some of the move in the afternoon as the 2y auction tails 2.2bp on weak demand. JGBs ultimately bull- flatten (2y: - 1bp; 30y: - 2bp). In Korea, KRW gains \(0.7\%\) against USD as BoK Governor Rhee highlights ongoing FX discussions with the US Treasury. Korean rates see modest moves after the BoK remains on hold at its August meeting, but sells off 2bp after Governor Rhee suggests that faster rate cuts could spur housing and debt risks, rather than growth. In the Philippines; PHP holds steady as the BSP lowers rates by 25bp, in line with expectations. PHP strengthens \(0.1\%\) against USD after BSP Governor Regolona states that the central bank may be nearing the end of its current easing cycle. In India's first trading session since \(50\%\) US tariffs took effect, INR shows little reaction (USD/INR: - 0.05%), suggesting the tariff implementation was largely priced beforehand. Indian rates rally (10y IGB: - 8bp) amid unconfirmed reports that the RBI has engaged with local banks that approached the RBI about taking action during debt sales, possibly via open market bond purchases.

Incorporating our forecast of a slight upward revision in core PCE for June (+2bp in m/m print), we expect the 3-month annualized pace at 3.08% (vs. 2.71% in June), the 6-month at 3.06% (vs. 3.21% prior), and the y/y rate at 2.91% (vs. 2.81% in June). We expect headline PCE rose 0.22% m/m and 2.66% y/y. While prices in goods more exposed to tariffs continued to increase, other less exposed goods categories fell, leaving core goods prices basically flat on the month (MSe 0.01% m/m). We expect services prices accelerated in July. We are now tracking core services ex-housing at 0.38% m/m.

We think gold flows added about \$11bn to the trade gap in July, with other imports rising modestly (+0.5%) and exports slipping slightly. In total, we expect the trade gap widened to \$98bn. Gold flows won't affect 3Q GDP; the swings elsewhere in exports and imports are small.

- BoJ Board Member Nakagawa conveyed caution on the economic outlook, with limited details on the BoJ's internal views regarding the US economic path. She stated that "the global economy, including Japan, is heading toward a slowdown, and we want to assess the extent of that deceleration given the high uncertainty." See more

- Fed Governor Waller reiterated that "the FOMC should not wait until the labor market deteriorates" to cut rates. He does not "believe that a cut of larger than 25 basis points is needed in September," but suggests that view could change if the August employment report "points to a substantially weakening economy and inflation remains well contained." Waller says he anticipates "additional cuts over the next three to six months, and the pace of rate cuts will be driven by the incoming data."

- In Korea, BoK maintained its policy rate at 2.50% at its August meeting (MSe: 2.25%; C: 2.50%; P: 2.50%), citing modest improvement in the growth outlook and the need to further monitor movements in house prices and household debt. The BoK revised its 2025 growth forecast slightly higher to 0.9% y/y (P: 0.8%) on the back of a sustained modest recovery in domestic demand as exports gradually slow, while keeping the 2026 growth forecast unchanged at 1.6%. The inflation forecasts were also revised modestly higher, with 2025 headline and core CPI at 2.0% y/y (P: 1.9%) and 1.9% y/y (P: 1.9%) respectively, and 2026 headline and core CPI at 1.9% (P: 1.8%) due to
the continued recovery in consumption. Read more

- BoK Governor Rhee revealed that one board member proposed cutting rates due to a cooling housing market and Fed easing risks. He added that 5 of 6 board members are open to a rate cut within the next 3 months, up from 4 members at the last meeting. He noted faster rate cuts may spur housing and debt risks more than growth, and reiterated further cuts are dependent on growth and financial stability. He estimated that the cumulative 100bp of rate cuts may have boosted growth by 24bp, adding that potential growth may be below 2% due to aging and other structural factors. Rhee stated that FX discussions are ongoing with the US Treasury, and the BoK's FX interventions in the past 1-2 years aimed to limit KRW depreciation, a move which the US may view as "desirable". Rhee said the outcome of the US-Korea summit did not warrant a revision to the growth outlook.

- In the Philippines, BSP lowered its policy rate by 25bp to 5.00% at its August meeting, as widely expected (MSE: 5.00%; C: 5.00%; P: 5.25%). The central bank said that inflation expectations remain well-anchored and the outlook for inflation is broadly unchanged, projecting inflation at 1.7% for 2025, 3.3% for 2026, and 3.4% for 2027. It flagged upside risks from possible electricity rate adjustments and higher rice tariffs. BSP noted that domestic demand has been firm, but external headwinds from global trade policies may temper the growth outlook for the Philippines.

- BSP Governor Remolona stated there is room for another rate cut in 2025, and it may be the last in the current easing cycle. He said the latest data puts the Philippines at the sweet spot for both inflation and output, and the policy rate is also "at our Goldilocks rate, neither too high nor too low". He characterized the BSP's stance as "still dovish but slightly less so than before." He added that the BSP is moving away from short-dated issuance.
- In Egypt, the CBE lowered its policy rate by 200bp to 22% in a larger-than-expected rate cut (MSE: 22.5%; C: 23.0%; P: 24.0%)

- US Q2 GDP Second Estimate: 3.3% q/q (MSE: 3.1%; C: 3.1%; P: 3.0%). The second estimate of US GDP comes in slightly above expectations. Personal consumption revised up from 1.4% to 1.6%. No adjustment in PCE inflation, headline or core. Fixed investment revised up to 3.3% from 0.4%. The decline in structures was reduced (-8.9%; P: -10.3%). IP was revised sharply higher to 12.8% (P: 6.4%). Equipment spending was also revised sharply higher, with final sales to domestic purchasers jumping to 1.6% (P: 1.1%). This suggests the economy grew about 1.5% in 1H 25, still signalling a moderating economy, though not as sharply as suggested by the advance estimate. Finally, the first estimate of gross domestic income rebounded sharply in Q2, rising 4.8% q/q in real terms. The significant rise in GDI (4.8% q/q saar) appears to be driven mainly by "Taxes on production and imports." This category rose \$230bn in the quarter and reflects public-sector tariff revenue.

When the 5- day moving average crosses above the 20- day moving average, buy the futures contract (long duration) and hold for a 25- business- day period. When the 5- day moving average crosses below the 20- day moving average, buy the futures contract and hold for a 25- business- day period. In short, this strategy buys futures when the Simple Moving Average Crossover (SMAX) generates both a long and a short signal, given the historical outperformance of long signals traded long and the underperformance of short signals traded short. Given that the SMAX could generate both a long and a short signal within the predefined holding period, an investor may have a 200% long position since each of the two signals would be traded in separate portfolio sleeves.
